<TEXT>
the governor offered on tuesday to lead 
negotiations aimed at ending a twoday walkout at staterun general 
hospital that had national guardsmen in combat fatigues caring for 
hundreds of patients 
gov edward d diprete made the offer to joseph g fargnoli 
president of the union representing the hospitals nurses and 
attendants as the two met privately for about an hour said nanci 
martin dipretes spokeswoman 
the governors going to hold a meeting at 10 am tomorrow in 
his office for both sides martin said previous negotiations have 
seen dipretes aides shuttling between both sides but this meeting 
would be face to face she said 
fargnoli made no commitment to diprete that the workers would 
return martin said fargnoli still had to report to the unions 
executive committee which would decide on further action union 
spokesman henry griggs said 
earlier tuesday a judge gave the strikers 24 hours to end their 
walkout the second job action in three weeks in a dispute over 
staffing superior court judge antonio s almeida granted the 
states request for a backtowork order citing a risk of 
irreparable harm to patients 
diprete called out the national guard on sunday for the second 
time in three weeks after a walkout by scores of workers over 
staffing levels talks broke down friday 
state officials had warned that patients lives were threatened 
and hospital administrator james p benedict said he was ready to 
empty out entire units 
the governor visited the hospital and said he was willing to keep 
the guard on duty as long as they need people here he said he 
was satisfied with the patient care 
sixtyeight guardsmen including seven with nursing training 
were at the hospital benedict said about 40 were working at the 
neighboring institute of mental health where union workers also 
failed to show said a guard spokesman 
guardsmen spent much of their time bathing and feeding patients 
at the 480bed hospital which serves primarily chronically ill 
patients needing longterm care 
the guardsmen are paid an average of 60 per day said capt john 
loughlin a guard spokesman 
a fourday sickout by union members ended jan 31 when diprete 
called out the guard 
the workers are angry at what they claim is the states failure 
to fill vacancies the state in an effort to cut overtime costs 
has refused in many cases to bring in additional workers to replace 
employees who call in sick 
staffing is the prerogative of management diprete said 
were on the threshold of what will be a milestone of philosophy 
of who operates the hospital 
benedict said 16 acutecare patients had been moved to other 
hospitals and six more would be shipped out about 410 patients 
were at the hospital 
ill be contacting more facilities than ive contacted already 
in hopes of appealing to them to take patients more rapidly for 
us the hospital director said we could begin to empty out 
entire units if need be 
thirtytwo of 85 normally scheduled attendants were on duty for 
the morning and afternoon shift twentyfour of 32 nurses were on 
duty for the morning shift and 20 for the afternoon shift some 
workers had been held over from previous shifts 
any emergency can happen at any time so i feel the patients 
lives are in danger said hospital medical director dr rajnikant 
shah he said half the patients were in medical danger 
</TEXT>
