<TEXT>
a sharp earthquake struck beneath the 
pacific ocean about 120 miles southwest of alaska but apparently 
went unnoticed early today officials said 
alec medbery of the alaska tsunami warning center said the 
temblor hit at 125 am registering 58 on the openended richter 
scale 
medbery said he called the national weather service station in 
kodiak at the states southern edge but was told no one there felt 
the quake and the observatory received no calls of inquiry or 
reports of damage 
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion in which every 
increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude a 
reading of 65 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 
55 
a quake of 5 can cause considerable damage and one registering 6 
is capable of causing severe damage 
the 1964 alaska quake that killed 131 people measured 84 on the 
richter scale 
