<TEXT>
the supreme court today sidestepped deciding 
whether a criminal defendants right to be tried by his peers is 
violated when prosecutors disqualify potential jurors based on their 
race 
by a 72 vote the justices ruled against frank d teague 
sentenced to 30 years in prison for the armed robbery of a chicago 
supermarket and for the attempted murder of police officers shot 
after the robbery 
four justices one vote short of the majority needed to set 
binding legal precedent said teague should not be allowed to raise 
the representativejury issue 
the four led by justice sandra day oconnor said federal courts 
should not establish new constitutional guidelines when ruling on 
socalled habeas corpus appeals by criminal defendants 
such appeals attack a defendants state court conviction or 
sentence on grounds that federal constitutional rights were 
violated the appeals always follow unsuccessful state court appeals 
by the defendants 
the justices in 1986 ruled that prosecutors never may disqualify 
potential jurors based on their race the court said such tactics 
violate equalprotection rights 
but a subsequent decision strictly limited the retroactive effect 
of the 1986 ruling the court said previously that the 1986 ruling 
does not apply to convicted criminals who like teague had 
exhausted direct appeals in state courts prior to when the 1986 
ruling was announced 
teagues habeas corpus appeal did not raise the equalprotection 
issue but instead attacked a prosecutors exclusion of 10 potential 
black jurors on grounds that it violated teagues right to a jury 
selected from a crosssection of the community 
teague who is black was convicted in 1978 by an allwhite jury 
if teague were to win on the fair crosssection challenge he 
would be entitled to a new trial even though the high courts 1986 
ruling came too late to help him 
past supreme court rulings have applied the sixth amendments 
fair crosssection requirement to pools of potential jurors but not 
to juries actually selected 
oconnor said the court should not decide whether the fair 
crosssection requirement applies to selected juries as well because 
that ruling could not apply to teague 
her opinion was joined by chief justice william h rehnquist and 
justices antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy 
justices byron r white harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
also voted to uphold teagues conviction but for differing reasons 
justices william j brennan and thurgood marshall dissented 
the case is teague vs lane 875259 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

