<TEXT>
big city life has certain drawbacks whether 
your home is new york city or moscow according to a recent joint 
survey of residents of those and other metropolises 
for instance 33 percent of muscovites and 38 percent of new 
yorkers said they were afraid to go out alone at night on the street 
where they lived 
in addition 38 percent of the moscow residents were unhappy with 
their public transportation as were 36 percent of those surveyed in 
new york twothirds of the muscovites and 64 percent of the new 
yorkers gave their local schools a grade of c d or f 
surveys of sentiments in moscow new york boston detroit and 
san francisco were sponsored by american news media from those 
cities and conducted in moscow with the help of the soviet institute 
of sociology results were reported in late january and early 
february by the sponsoring news organizations 
soviet and american polling experts held a briefing here 
wednesday to shed light on such mysteries as why virtually none of 
the muscovites owned up to heavy drinking and why 17 percent never 
heard of the marxist leader of nicaragua 
about 1000 people each were surveyed by telephone in december in 
moscow and new york and 600 in each of the other us cities the 
surveys had a threepoint margin of error for the moscow and new 
york results and four points for the other cities 
several american reporters veterans of moscow assignments who 
recalled lines outside staterun liquor stores questioned the 
credibility of any survey that depicted muscovites as abstemious 
when asked how often they drank alcohol not even 1 percent of 
the moscow residents said they drank almost every day 5 percent 
responded once or twice a week 17 percent said once or twice a 
month 41 percent said several times a year and 36 percent said 
never 
by contrast 12 percent of the san franciscans 9 percent of 
bostonians 6 percent of new yorkers and 5 percent of detroiters 
owned up to drinking almost daily 
nobody accepted the not drinking figures from moscow on 
face value said john marttila of the boston polling firm of 
marttila amp kiley inc which undertook the surveys with market 
opinion research 
elena bashkirova of the institute of sociology in moscow said the 
soviet antialcoholism drive may be working she also suggested that 
soviets may drink on fewer occasions than americans but more 
heavily 
the surveys found that 67 to 79 percent of the us citizens said 
they were very proud to be americans and 18 to 22 percent of 
the rest were quite proud of their country in moscow 39 
percent said they were very proud to be a soviet citizen and 38 
percent were quite proud 
sixtynine percent of the muscovites said they never went out to 
dinner at a restaurant only 4 to 7 percent of the americans said 
they never dined out a third to a half of the americans said they 
dined out once or twice a week compared with 2 percent of the 
muscovites 
twentythree percent of the muscovites never heard of irans 
ayatollah ruhollah khomeini 25 percent never heard of pope john 
paul ii 38 percent knew nothing of libyas moammar gadhafi and 17 
percent were in the dark about nicaraguas daniel ortega 
that surprised us most of all with the level of attention to 
daniel ortega who is every day on soviet television news or mass 
media said bashkirovas colleague valeriy korobeinikov it shows 
people set their own priorities when listening to world news he 
said 
the surveys were funded by the new york daily news wcbstv and 
wcbs radio in new york wcvbtv in boston the detroit free press 
and krontv in san francisco 
