<TEXT>
the energy department cannot complete a major 
analysis of its three idled tritium production reactors at savannah 
river sc before the first one is ready to be restarted a 
department adviser told congress on wednesday 
its probably going to take a lot longer than a year to prove 
that the reactors can safely withstand the most serious plausible 
accident they are expected to face john ahearne told the energy and 
power subcommittee of the house energy and commerce committee 
ahearne a former member of the nuclear regulatory commission is 
chairman of the departments advisory committee on nuclear 
facilities safeguards 
department officials have testified in other hearings that they 
hoped to restart one of the reactors by the end of 1989 this 
restart date has been getting later and later at one point last 
fall the department was saying it hoped to restart one reactor by 
the end of 1988 
when all the other work is complete the secretary of energy will 
have to decide whether to permit the restart weighing the need for 
tritium against the incompleteness of the analysis 
tritium is an essential ingredient in many of the nations 
nuclear weapons it must be replenished every few years because 55 
percent of any starting amount decays in the course of a year just 
when the power of the weapons would decay to an unacceptable point 
is a secret but the boston globe recently reported that pentagon 
officials had said an 18month or twoyear pause in tritium 
production might be tolerable 
the department ordered the savannah river reactors closed last 
year for safety and management upgrading after the operator du pont 
co brought the only active one into full operation at half power 
despite an unexplained power surge during startup 
the most serious plausible accident is what the civilian nuclear 
power industry calls the design basis accident that is the 
worst accident the plant designers have taken into account 
such a hypothetical accident would vary according to the plant 
design and site for instance in one place it might be a tornado 
in another it might be an earthquake 
the savannah river reactors are supposed to be able to shut down 
safely on emergency cooling even if they suffer a double 
guillotine break of a main cooling system pipe a complete break 
in two places that removes a section of pipe and cuts normal coolant 
flow to zero 
until recently ahearne said they have not had the analytical 
capability in the department to prove by calculation that the 
reactors would be safe in such a case 
in 1986 the department cut reactor operations to 75 percent of 
full power because of uncertainty that such a break could be 
handled after a national research council report calling attention 
to the uncertainties the following year power was limited to 50 
percent 
my conclusion is i dont think they are going to have the 
analysis done when theyr ready to restart and thats where the 
subjective judgment of the secretary comes in ahearne said in 
an interview after the hearing 
the nuclear regulatory commission sometimes has permitted 
civilian power plants to start operation before the analysis of the 
design basis accident has been completed if it judged the 
probability of such a accident sufficiently low ahearne said 
its not that unusual in the commercial world he said 
such an analysis is enormously complicated mathematically and 
sometimes cannot be completed until computer models are checked 
against experiments in actual scale models of sections of the 
reactor piping 
chris sankey spokeswoman for the energy department said 
department officials wanted to give james watkins nominated to be 
energy secretary a chance after his expected confirmation to get up 
to speed on all restart issues before it addresses comments like 
ahearnes 
