<TEXT>
james d watkins the designated energy 
secretary told congress wednesday he would assemble within six 
months the nucleus of a new management team to shake up a nuclear 
weapons complex desperately in need of change 
the retired admiral in seeking to become the first career 
military man to head the energy department since it was created in 
1977 also vowed to tackle an array of conventional energy problems 
including growing dependence on foreign oil 
watkins won warm praise from nearly every member of the senate 
energy and natural resources committee during his three hours of 
testimony j bennett johnston dla the committee chairman set a 
vote on the nomination for next wednesday 
watkins 61 spent four decades in the navy capping his career 
with a fouryear stint as chief of naval operations in 1987 he led 
a presidential aids commission to a series of widely praised 
recommendations on what to do about the deadly disease 
he was closely associated with the navys nuclear program but has 
no experience in the conventional energy field which he has called 
his achilles heel 
you come to us with a certain luster said sen howard m 
metzenbaum dohio a strong critic of the energy departments 
handling of the 17site complex in 12 states that develops produces 
and tests the nations nuclear weapons 
the weapons plants key parts of which were built in the 1940s 
and 1950s to develop the worlds first atomic bombs have been 
breaking down in recent months exposing flaws in safety procedures 
technical standards and management widespread contamination of soil 
and groundwater also has been discovered estimates for correcting 
the problems range from 81 billion to 155 billion 
problems relating to safety health and the environment have 
not only been backlogged to intolerable levels but in effect 
hidden from public view until recently watkins said 
he called the energy departments management system antique 
out of date and desperately in need of change he said he 
would put together the fundamental embryo of a new management 
team to impose major changes on the nuclear complex 
the weapons plants are run for the energy department by private 
contractors watkins said the department historically has put too 
much emphasis on meeting nuclear production goals at the expense of 
safety and the environment 
i will organize a management team that understands how to 
motivate people how to achieve and reward excellence and how to 
reject and deal firmly and fairly and swiftly with incompetence 
watkins said 
under the existing department management there is little risk 
in being careless little incentive to excel he said adding that 
he would seek to instill a work attitude that would allow the 
department to regain its public credibility 
watkins was not asked whether he supports the departments 
existing blueprint for modernizing and cleaning up the nuclear 
weapons complex that report issued shortly before president reagan 
left office last month proposed a series of controversial actions 
to revitalize the complex over the next 21 years it put the cleanup 
and modernization cost at 81 billion over that period 
on other subjects watkins said he would 
seek to limit the nations reliance on foreign oil by promoting 
a wide array of actions including using federal funds to develop 
the technology to burn clean coal open up more federal lands to 
oil exploration and give oil drillers new tax breaks 
support efforts mainly by private industry to develop 
methanol or wood alcohol as an alternative to gasoline this would 
sharply reduce the need for crude oil 
try to increase the pool of talent in the energy department and 
to promote creativity in its staff he said his number one 
objective was leading the department to higher standards of 
personal excellence among the work force 
