japan successfully launched a research satellite 
wednesday from its space center at tanegashima authorities said 
the launch went smoothly and the satellite named exosd entered 
its orbit as planned said the official from the institute of space 
and astronautical science 
exosd the 12th scientific satellite launched by the 
governmentsponsored agency will study the earths auroras and 
their relationship to plasma particles emitted by the sun she said 
auroras are luminous displays usually seen around the north and 
south poles believed to be caused by collisions of charged 
particles from the sun and oxygen and nitrogen atoms in the earths 
atmosphere the 660pound satellite contains eight devices to study 
and photograph auroras and plasma waves the official said 
the satellites elliptical orbit is expected to range from 250 
miles to 6250 miles 
japan limits its rocket launches to only 90 days a year 45 days 
in july and august and 45 days in january and february because of 
protests from tuna fishermen in the area of the space center off 
japans southern main island of kyushu the fishermen say rocket 
launches are dangerous 
japan entered the aerospace field late because of restrictions 
imposed by us occupation forces after world war ii but has 
advanced quickly in recent years with a high success rate 
