<TEXT>
a team of government and private veterinarians 
has cleared the navy of allegations it mistreated dolphins and sea 
lions being trained for various underwater surveillance duties 
the marine mammal commission review team after what it described 
as an extensive survey of navy facilities and practices sharply 
criticized a former navy trainer and other unidentified sources who 
charged last november the service was guilty of animal abuse 
the review team found the allegations to be substantively 
lacking states the commissions report released wednesday by the 
navy 
the team concluded that allegations had been put forward in 
such a way as to create an inaccurate picture the report 
continued 
furthermore the team concluded that had the sole motivation 
underlying the allegations been concern for the health welfare and 
care of the animals the former trainer would have made better use 
than he did of the navys animal care committee 
the program now includes about 115 animals the majority of them 
dolphins and the remainder of them beluga whales the service trains 
the mammals to detect enemy scuba divers and to hunt for underwater 
mines the program began more than 20 years ago 
the washingtonbased marine mammal commission which advises all 
federal agencies on the handling of marine mammals ordered an 
investigation after former navy trainer rick trout charged last 
november he had witnessed incidents of abuse weight loss 
corporal punishment and damage to animals after transport 
trout who no longer works for the navy made the allegations 
during an appearance before the international marine animal trainers 
association meeting in san antonio texas 
to investigate the charges the commission appointed a 
sevenmember review team that included veterinarians or medical 
doctors from the agriculture department the national marine 
fisheries services various university faculties and the chicago 
zoological society 
none of the members had ties to the navy 
after conducting lengthy interviews with trout and other former 
navy employees and then inspecting navy facilities and records the 
review team concluded 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a navy dolphin that died after being transported to the persian 
gulf did not succumb to poor training mistreatment mishandling 
or changes in water temperature the dolphin died of bronchial 
pneumonia 
there is no evidence that the nutritional program as it 
presently exists has adversely affected the health and welfare of 
the animals and certainly no evidence of intentional starvation 
the only trainer ever observed using food to bait a dolphin 
during training or dumping fish outside a netted pen as punishment 
was the person making the allegations 
there have been only two isolated incidents within the past 
three years of a trainer slapping or striking a dolphin and in both 
cases the trainers were immediately disciplined 
during the last 22 months three dolphins have died at the 
navys mammal center in san diego the deaths were not related to 
improper training poor handling techniques or inadequate veterinary 
care 
and there is no evidence of animals having been blinded or 
injured or as a result of poor training procedures 
the team did not give the navy a completely clean bill of health 
for example it concluded the navys san diego facility where 
trout worked did a better job than a facility in hawaii of 
ensuring that veterinarians supervised all aspects of care and 
training 
it also criticized delays in the hiring of two additional 
fulltime veterinarians and noted that in the past there has been 
one highlevel person within the pentagon responsible for the marine 
mammal program 
that does not appear to be the case now the team recommends 
that such an assignment be made 
all in all though the navy is following or exceeding federal 
guidelines for the proper handling of marine mammals the team said 
and in some areas such as the ratio of trainers and veterinarians 
to animals and medical care standards and recordkeeping the navys 
performance is as good as or better than in other institutions 
