he said defendants were convicted but their life sentences were 
overturned on appeal because prosecutors had used a state law to 
obtain convictions and state laws do not apply to crimes on indian 
reservations 
in another trial he said prosecutors searched federal statutes 
for provisions referring to rape and while such a crime against 
females was covered similar acts on males were not in his sons 
case a defendant pleaded guilty last spring to assault causing 
bodily harm and got a 10year sentence blythe said 
he said federal statutes have since been amended for cases such 
as those involving his children but that similar loopholes likely 
exist for other types of crimes 
burnley said that since that federal law was amended in 1986 
many more cases of sex abuse on reservations have come to light but 
arranging help for victims has been difficult 
