all nippon airways of japan announced wenesday 
an order for 20 boeing 747400s and said negotiations are underway 
for boeing 767s that could raise the total value of the two deals to 
as much as 475 billion 
the sale of 747400s for delivery beginning in 1992 came despite 
boeings inability to meet delivery deadlines for the sophisticated 
jumbo jets to other airlines company chairman f a shrontz said 
the seattlebased company hopes to get back on schedule with a new 
delivery plan 
the order added to six 747400s ana ordered in october makes 
the airline the biggest purchaser of the new model japan air lines 
ordered 20 of the same model in july 1987 british airways ordered 
19 in august 1986 
only one 747400 has been delivered to northwest airlines the 
new model takes a smaller crew has a new wing design saves fuel 
can fly further and can be equipped to carry more passengers than 
the 747300 boeing now has 192 orders for the new plane 
all nippon japans largest airline with 102 planes announced at 
a news conference with boeing officials that it will pay 315 
billion for the 747s including spare parts and general electric 
engines the planes are to be used on both domestic and new 
expanding international routes with delivery of from four to six a 
year between 1992 and 1996 
the 747 sale alone is equal to 57 percent of last years us 
trade deficit with japan ana officials noted 
sigeya goto ana executive vice president said the company is 
also negotiating with boeing to purchase 15 to 20 boeing 767s at a 
cost of 12 billion to 16 billion they would also be delivered 
beginning in 1992 
ana flies more than 27 million passengers a year on 66 domestic 
routes and on international flights to washington dc los 
angeles beijing and dalian china guam sydney seoul and hong 
kong 
next year goto said the airline plans to add flights from tokyo 
to bangkok vienna moscow london and stockholm ana became an 
international airline in 1986 with flights to guam he said the 
airline expects a 30 percent increase in international passengers 
this year 
thanks to the healthy yen japanese citizens are travelling the 
world and consumer demand is increasing steadily he said 
goto said the airline is satisfied boeing has implemented new 
manufacturing procedures that would overcome problems the 
manufacturer has had with miswiring in new aircraft he said that 
with the big order double the number of japanese technicians would 
be sent and their stays at boeing plants would be longer in 
overseeing construction of planes ordered by the airlines 
the boeing chairman in a speech before the international 
aviation club after the announcement said delays in 747400 
deliveries have been a disappointment to us 
shrontz said other purchasers are being advised of a new delivery 
schedule 
we looked at the situation the magnitude of the work that was 
ahead of us and decided we would sacrifice schedule to make sure 
that the product that comes out is a quality and defectfree 
product shrontz said 
he said that recent incidents of crosswiring found in the 
emergency systems of several boeing airliners were not due to the 
push to produce 
i will not say it was isolated because we had more than one i 
will say it tended to be random and i dont think it reflects on any 
quality deterioration its clear we did not do an adequate job in 
preventing defects in the system shrontz said 
he said the problem has been fixed and i dont think youll 
see any more of that 
the 747400 includes a stretched upper deck similar to the one on 
the 747300 but can be equipped to carry up to 509 passengers 
instead of 496 for the earlier model alternatively it can be 
outfitted with extra fuel capacity to give it a range of about 8000 
miles which is 1000 miles further 
the new model also have sixfoot winglets that improve fuel 
economy but extend upward at the ends of the wing so the airliners 
do not take up any more space 
