<TEXT>
here is a look at laws in the 10 states and the district of 
columbia that have laws requiring some form of recycling 
rhode island residents must separate newspapers and rinsed cans 
and bottles into containers for pickup 
new jersey residents must separate recyclable materials 
municipalities have until end of 1989 to recycle 25 percent of 
garbage 
pennsylvania residents must separate recyclables goal is 25 
percent recycling by 1997 
oregon municipalities with populations over 4000 must provide 
dropoff centers and make curbside collection of recyclables at 
least once a month 
district of columbia offices must recycle paper and newspaper 
and residents must recycle newspaper and yard waste by oct 1 
residents and businesses will have to separate metals and glass by 
the end of 1990 
connecticut recyclable materials are banned from landfills 
state is setting up six recycling centers 
florida counties must have recycling programs in place by july 
plastic foodpackaging materials are banned unless they degrade 
within specified times goal is 30 percent recycling 
maryland counties have been ordered to create recycling plans 
goal is 20 percent recycling for counties with more than 150000 
people 
hawaii residents must be given the opportunity to recycle with 
collection centers and monthly curbside pickup in urban areas but 
law says recyclable materials cannot cost more to collect and sell 
than to collect and dispose of 
illinois chicago and large counties are required to develop 
comprehensive waste management plans emphasizing recycling and 
landfilling within two years goal is 25 percent recycling in seven 
years 
new york municipalities have until sept 1 1992 to establish 
programs requiring residents to separate recyclable materials that 
do not cost more to collect and sell than to collect and dispose 
</TEXT>
