<TEXT>
the nightmare on ad street isnt invincible movie 
fiend freddy krueger but to the advertising industry its just as 
threatening 
this nightmare is state taxes on advertising which have been 
proposed in several states despite the ad industrys major victory 
over floridas ad tax 
fifteen months after a storm of industry criticism forced florida 
to repeal its shortlived and controversial 5 percent tax on 
advertising and a host of other services ad trade groups nervously 
are eyeing connecticut 
the head of the connecticut legislatures taxwriting committee 
says he wants to tax advertising and predicts success there could 
prompt similar taxes in neighboring new york massachusetts and 
rhode island 
its the most threatening situation we have faced since the 
florida fight said dan jaffe who heads the washington office of 
the association of national advertisers a trade and lobbying group 
legislation that advertisers fear could lead to a tax on 
advertising is before a legislative committee in missouri but is not 
expected to go any further foes killed a diiluted advertising sales 
tax plan applying only to political ads earlier this month in 
south dakota 
and in oregon state revenue officials have withdrawn their 
support for a proposal to tax broadcasting companies on the basis of 
viewership in the state 
nonetheless advertisers their agencies and media buyers say 
they must remain vigilant because budgetary pressures are growing in 
many states 
advertisers argue that taxing advertising will make products more 
expensive and depress sales cutting into state tax revenue 
they say taxing advertising would reduce the amount of 
information that gets out to consumers about products and warn that 
states with such taxes risk driving out business and national ad 
spending 
but those arguments are engendering less sympathy in some 
cashstrapped states where a few lawmakers say taxing activities 
such as advertising is preferable to spending cuts and general tax 
hikes 
there is no reason i can see that they should be excluded from 
the tax said sen william dibella a hartford democrat who is 
backing a proposal to subject advertising to the 75 percent sales 
and use tax in connecticut 
dibella chairs the committee that will conduct a hearing next 
month on the proposal terms of which are still being drafted he 
estimated that taxing advertising could generate 110 million to 
120 million annually and said the committee may earmark proceeds 
for politicallyappealing efforts to combat drugs and crime 
dibella said in a telephone interview that he has visited 
lawmakers in florida several times to discuss their experience in 
taxing advertising and other services and said he thinks a similar 
tax could work in connecticut 
the florida tax situation attracted national attention because it 
taxed outofstate services used by floridians companies buying 
advertisements in magazines or the broadcast networks for instance 
were required to pay a tax based on circulation or viewership in 
florida 
the tax enacted in july 1987 was repealed six months later amid 
an outcry that saw ad trade groups cancel conventions planned in the 
state and national advertisers threaten to cut florida ad spending 
dibella said he is unimpressed with arguments that companies 
would quit advertising in connecticut or move out of state if 
advertising were taxed 
this state has one of the highest per capita incomes in the 
nation and i doubt that anybody is going to turn their backs on 
that he said 
in missouri two bills are pending in committee that would end 
exemptions for advertising and a number of other items from the 
state sales tax 
but the sponsor of one of the bills rep karen mccarthy a 
kansas city democrat who chairs the panel handling both measures 
said by telephone she has no intention of moving either bill any 
further this year 
earlier this month a plan to impose the south dakota state sales 
tax on advertising was killed in the state house even after being 
amended to apply only to political advertising 
in oregon the state department of revenue recently withdrew its 
support for a proposal to change the way the state taxes the profits 
of broadcasting companies to include oregon viewership as part of 
the calculation 
jim brown a state revenue official said the department changed 
its mind about the bill due to opposition from local broadcasters 
and a judgment that the proposal was illtimed he said the bill 
probably was dead for the session 
