<TEXT>
massachusetts leading an effort by the 
northeastern states to dramatically reduce smogcausing gasoline 
emissions sued the environmental protection agency on wednesday for 
delaying action on the states gasoline volatility regulations 
if the epa cant take the lead in forging an aggressive new 
national environmental policy then the very least they can do is 
get out of the way when states like massachusetts take the 
initiative attorney general james shannon said 
the suit asks the epa for an immediate decision on the 
regulations 
the state department of environmental quality engineering 
proposed rules last may requiring gasoline manufacturers to 
reformulate gasoline sold in massachusetts primarily by eliminating 
a butane additive during the summer to reduce smogcausing 
emissions 
under the regulations which massachusetts hoped to impose this 
year gasoline sold in the commonwealth between may 1 and sept 15 
must have a reid vapor pressure of 9 pounds per square inch or less 
compared with the 115 psi common now 
rvp is the measure of a gasolines volatility the lower the rvp 
the less the gasoline evaporates vapors that contribute to the 
formulation of groundlevel ozone 
currently only california has such standards which received epa 
approval since the 1970s but following massachusetts action 
connecticut maine new jersey rhode island and vermont passed 
similar regulations and now all are waiting to see what happens with 
massachusetts application to the epa to implement the gasoline 
restrictions 
each individual state must receive epa approval before the 
regulations can take effect 
massachusetts which had a record 53 days last summer in which 
its air quality exceeded federal health standards from cape cod to 
the western part of the state estimates its gasoline regulations 
could reduce the amount of volatile organic compounds in the air by 
9000 tons a year 
officials have estimated the restrictions implemented regionwide 
could reduce these compounds by more than 150000 tons annually in 
the northeast 
massachusetts submitted its regulations for epa review in july 
in the suit filed wednesday in us district court in boston 
shannon alleged the agency failed to meet federal clean air act 
guidelines requiring a decision in four months 
we have admittedly taken longer than this four months although 
it is arguable whether the four months is a mandatory requirement or 
not epa regional administrator michael deland said in an 
interview 
deland said his office told shannon in explicit terms and this 
was prior to our realization that he was going to be filing a suit 
we would process the massachusetts application by this summers 
ozone season 
delands air quality chief steve perkins said massachusetts 
regulations will be published in the federal register on thursday 
beginning a 30day comment period before the epa and then the office 
of management and budget can make a ruling 
deland said that he personally favors massachusetts regulations 
but he said other factors to consider include whether the state 
regulations would conflict with epas proposal to set a national rvp 
standard of 105 psi under the epas plan the national standard 
would not reach massachusetts 90 psi limit until 1992 
deland said the oil industry contends it will be forced to 
produce more gasoline if it has to eliminate the butane additive 
that commonly makes up about 2 percent of the gasoline sold to 
motorists 
the oil refining industry has said that they are at maximum 
production right now deland said and are predicting all sorts 
of dire consequences come summer under massachusetts plan namely 
gasoline shortages and escalation in gasoline prices 
deland said the massachusetts limit needs to be done in a 
measured way 
